Name: B.1.1.7
Comment:
Possess about %50 increased transmission
Severity increased based on hospitalization and case fatality rates
No impact on susceptibility to EUA monoclonal antibody treatments
BNT162b2 mRNA vaccine has efficacy between 85.9–92.3 (89.5) after second dose
Minimal effect on neutralization by convalescent and post-vaccination sera.
It is also reported that the Oxford–AstraZeneca COVID-19 vaccine had an efficacy of 42–89% against the B.1.1.7 variant, whereas it does 71–91% against non-B.1.1.7 variants.
A clinical study indicates that the Novavax vaccine is ~96% effective for symptoms against the original variant and~86% against B.1.1.7.

Name: P.1
Comment:
K417T, E484K, and N501Y are the mutations present in the receptor binding domains.
Substantial decrease in susceptibility to the combination of bamlanivimab and etesevimab monoclonal antibody treatment
Other EUA monoclonal antibody treatments are available
Reduced neutralization by convalescent and post-vaccination sera
With Sinovac antibody levels reduced.
P.1 variant is capable of partially escaping vaccination with the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine

Name: B.1.351
Comment:
Transmissibility increased at about 50%
Remarkable decline in susceptibility to the combination of bamlanivimab and etesevimab monoclonal antibody treatment
Yet other EUA monoclonal antibody treatments are available
Reduced neutralization due to convalescent and post-vaccination sera
Effectiveness of BNT162b2 mRNA vaccine is between 70.5–78.9 (75.0)
K417N, E484K, N501Y substitutions are some of the mutations in the spike protein.
No evidence that reports whether it has impact on disease severity.
Lastly, Pfizer/BioNTech South African vaccine trial stated that the vaccine was 100% effective

Name: B.1
Origin: European early 2020 (speculated as end of January)
Comment:
A large European lineage the origin of which roughly corresponds to the Northern Italian outbreak early in 2020.
Lineage B.1 is the predominant known global lineage and has been subdivided into >70 sublineages.
All variants in B.1 clade share one specific mutation called D614G.
This mutation was one of the first documented in the US in the initial stages of the pandemic, after having initially circulated in Europe.
There is evidence that variants with this mutation (D614G) spread more quickly than viruses without this mutation.
Although this variant causes increased infectivity, it is associated with decreased clinical severity in several reports.
Variant_Type: main monophyletic group so that it can be classified as both concern or interest due to various sublineages.

Name: C.37
Comment: Novel lineage expanding in Peru and Chile, with a convergent deletion in the ORF1a gene (?3675-3677) and a novel deletion in the Spike gene (?246-252, G75V, T76I, L452Q, F490S, T859N).
